In the first scenario, the two coworker know each other well and therefore should know that one makes coffee.  In the second, it isn't likely that the same knowledge exists.

Bob observed Dan make coffee every day while he did not. So Bob of course assumed he wouldn't make coffee on Friday either. So I blame Bob there for being unpredictable.  If you're talking about the first scenario also, neither knew what the other did normally. It would be prudent for noone to make coffee, so I blamed both of them equally.

In both videos, each people are equally at fault because they are both microwaving at the same time. Knowledge that someone is likely (or not) using a microwave has no impact on the fault. They both performed the action that caused the fault.

the first two knew each other's schedule so they should have an idea on how to avoid a power failure.

eddie and neil dont know each other at all there's no reason to expect them to know how to avoid a power failure.

(... other than the company wide policy... of course... ... ...)

I made judgments based on what the two people knew about the other persons microwave usage. The first story the two knew each others habits so there shouldn't be any power failure. The second story the two workers didn't know each others habits, so it's understandable why there was a power failure.

The pair who knew each other could've avoided the situation if they just picked up the phone or texted; they're equally at fault.  The pair who didn't know each other cannot be held responsible for the actions of the other.
column111: I'm not sure why you asked about the second pair's expectations about microwave use when they don't even know each other.  Maybe that's the way it's supposed to be, I guess.

column110: Workers are not responsible for stupid policies. Technically they both caused the outage, but the employer contribution to this problem is also substantial.
